I'm not sure if it's simply a Boston mass and surrounding city thing, But it seems to me that people here dont really put a premium on customer service. I walked in this restaurant for the first time ever , asked for a menu and was directed to the overhead Menu as I guess there were no paper menus available.  I looked over the menu as the employees 3 of them, were engaged in a conversation, in Spanish of course.  Once I was ready to order I stood there for no less than 45 seconds as they continued to talk and laugh. Doesn't seem like a long time with one key point, it's a service business where there's a customer waiting to order who hasn't been acknowledged.  I've been in the people business for over twenty years and I believe no matter what your service business is, the customer should never leave feeling like your doing them a favor. I would never patronize this business again and they probably dont even care.  SAD BUT TRUE.

I love the food here, which is why it gets two stars instead of one. And I’m never coming back to this location.  This week I have had to drive to my daughter’s school at her lunchtime every day. On Tuesday I called in an order for pick-up and brought it back to work. On wednesday I came in, ordered and ate.  Those days were fine, and I enjoyed my food.  Today, after my lunchtime errand, I called Tenoch to order a burrito to go. The lady picked up the phone and said, “Just a sec.”  I held, driving (safely, thank you) toward Medford Square. I held. I held some more. I could hear her ringing in orders and taking payment from other customers. I arrived in Medford Square and parked my car in one of the very rare non-metered spots. I was still on hold. At this point I was morbidly curious. I walked into the restaurant, still on hold, and got in line. After nearly nine minutes on hold, the lady at the register saw that the phone was off the hook—and hung up on me.  When I got to the fellow taking orders, I said, “I’d like to speak to the manager, please.” He looked at the other man making food with him, had a brief exchange in Spanish, and referred me to her.  “You hung up on me,” I said. “I was busy. I’m just one person and I was busy,” she said defensively. “But I called in, you said ‘just a sec’, and you didn’t pick up the phone again. I was on hold for nearly nine minutes!” “But I’m just one person, it was busy...”  She didn’t apologize. She didn’t promise to try improving her telephone skills. She didn’t offer anything to improve my mood, and frankly a sincere apology would have been fine. All she did was get defensive about how hard she was working with the customers in front of her. The customer calling in got ignored.  I walked out without ordering anything.  I work in customer service. I know how the pressure can be. And fast food, I’ve worked that too, including on the phones. I know the value of taking care of your customers and apologizing when you make a mistake or are accidentally rude.  This manager’s actions were not the epitome of rudeness, no, but to her, I did not matter as a customer. She was defending her rude service, without apology. Personally? I’m done.  I still love Tenoch’s food, but if I am going to have it again I’ll either go to their Somerville location or hunt up their food truck. The Medford location just showed me that they do not want my business.
